<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-12-23T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-12-23T08:00:00-05:00" n="883" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d883">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">493.11/12–2344: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Appointed Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-23T20:00:00+07:00">December 23,
                                1944—8 p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received December 25—12:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>2062. Political Vice Foreign Minister<note n="5" xml:id="d883fn5">K. C.
                            Wu.</note> has informed us that Executive Yuan has recommended to
                        National Defense Council that abolition of Boxer indemnity boards be
                        suspended and that therefore “China Foundation can carry on next year.”
                        (Reurtel 1626, December 12.) We shall expect to obtain additional
                        information and report further in due course.<note n="6" xml:id="d883fn6">Despatch No. 135, February 10, 1945, not printed.</note>
                    </p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hurley</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
            </body></text></TEI>